1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1187":"1187","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England"},"nl":{"1210–":"1210–Overleden","1210–Male":"1210–Overleden","1216–Female":"1216–Overleden","1235–Male":"1235–Overleden","1187–Male":"1187–Overleden","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1187":"1187","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"1210–":"1210–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1216–Female":"1216–Deceased","1235–Male":"1235–Deceased","1187–Male":"1187–Deceased","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1224":"1224","1210":"1210","1187":"1187","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fowke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name  <i>Folk</i>,  <i>Fulk</i>,  <i>Fuke</i>.  Compare  Foxon  . For a variant form of the personal name  see  Foulkes  .  See also  Fudge  , which may sometimes be a variant form."],"variants":[{"name":"Fudge","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulch</i> or <i>Fuche</i>, usually a pet form of Old French <i>Fulcher</i>, <i>Fucher</i> (see   Fulcher  ). Voicing of ‘ch’ to soft ‘g’ gave rise to <i>Fudge</i>. The name may sometimes have been interchangeable with <b>Fowke</b> (for which see   Foulk   1), derived from a pet form of this and other Old French personal names in <i>Fulc-</i>.","English: habitational name from Fuge, in Blackawton, Devon. This placename is composed of Old English <i>feoh</i> ‘cattle’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘farm, dairy farm, village’."]},{"name":"Folke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Fook","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Foulk","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulk</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, ultimately from an element meaning ‘folk, people’."]},{"name":"Fogg","meanings":["English (northern): possibly a variant of <b>Fowke</b> (see   Foulk   1). It may derive from Middle English <i>fogge</i> ‘aftermath’ (i.e. grass left to grow after the hay has been cut, also applied to long grass in a water meadow), especially in northern England, where the term occurs as a specifying element in minor placenames, but as it is not found on its own as a simplex name, the derivation is doubtful without some supporting evidence. The word <i>fogge</i>, which is probably of Old Norse origin, is still in use as a dialect term in Craven, Yorkshire, and in eastern Lancashire. modern English <i>fog</i> ‘thick mist’ is first attested in the 16th century and is unlikely to be the source of the surname."]},{"name":"Fuke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke   and  compare  Fook  ."]},{"name":"Folk","meanings":["German: variant of   Volk   1 and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in Czechia.","English: variant of   Foulk   1."]},{"name":"Focke","meanings":["North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Folco</i>, a pet form of various names beginning with <i>Folc-</i> or <i>Volk-</i>; cognate with   Foulk   1.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Foulk   1. See also   Foulks  ."]},{"name":"Foulke","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Shropshire): variant of   Foulk  ."]},{"name":"Fulk","meanings":["English: variant of   Foulk   1.","Altered form of German   Volk   or   Falk  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":49,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Fowke was born in 1210, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England as the son of Sir Henry Fowke. He had at least 1 son with Isabella West. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1210–":"1210–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1216–Female":"1216–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Sur